<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-573-026  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 573 026.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  August 22 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Int'l labor group slams robots. (International LabourOrganisation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dauchy, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International Labor OrganizationReportsRobotsAutomation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INT'L LABOR GROUP SLAMS ROBOTS GENEVA, SWITZERLAND, 1989 AUG 18 (NB) --Robots are considered perfect employees from an employer's point of view.andO;They do not strike, never eat, yet they work 24 hours a day and take onunsafe and unhealthy work from their human colleagues.andP;  Despite theseadvantages, the International Labour Organisation (ILO) has issued a reportwhich concludes that robots are too simple to be used safely.andP;  The ILO reportgoes as far as saying that robots can cause the death of humans.andP;  The ILOreport states that, whilst robots undoubtedly help to improve the workingconditions for humans, they add new risks to the list of working accidents.andO;The report cites the case of a Japanese worker who became entangled in thearms of an industrial robot, which killed him by crushing his head, despitethe fact he was wearing a safety helmet at the time.andP;  Out of ten fatalaccidents involving robots in Japan, four were found to have been the faultof a wrong command of the employee, whilst the remaining six were caused bythe robot going berserk.andP;  Japan has the highest number of robots (141,000)and has an average of five serious accidents a year involving them.andP;  Incomparison, the US Administration counted 17 cases of accidents withindustrial robots out a total robot workforce of 29,000 last year.andP;  InEurope, Sweden suffered 36 accidents between 1979 and 1983, the report said.andO;The ILO concludes that the primary reasons for robot malfunction areelectrical breakdowns, programming faults and the use of inflammable oil inthe system hydraulics.andP;  Accidents can also happen when unauthorized personsstray into a prohibited area, the report said.andP;  To counter these problems theILO advises nations to implement a range of safety measures.andP;  In order togive a helping hand in that direction, it listed the measures taken by Japan,the United States, Britain, East and West Germany, France and the SovietUnion.andP;  (Eric Dauchy/19890818)</TEXT></DOC>